Subjective.Chief_Complaint: Patient reports occasional backaches and some discomfort following a car accident in September.
Subjective.History_of_Present_Illness: Ms. Jones was involved in a car accident on September 1st, around 12:30 PM, while driving from Cheadle Hulme to Manchester. Her car was hit from behind, pushing it into the vehicle in front. She was wearing her seatbelt. Immediately after the impact, she experienced shock, hit her head on the steering wheel, and felt pain in her neck and back. She sought medical attention at Moss Bank Accident and Emergency, where she was diagnosed with a whiplash injury; no X-rays were performed. The first four weeks post-accident were characterized by severe neck and back pain, difficulty sleeping, and regular use of painkillers. Symptoms began improving after this period, and she underwent ten sessions of physiotherapy for stiffness and discomfort. Currently, she experiences occasional backaches, which are not constant and significantly less severe than initially. She denies any anxiety while driving, difficulty concentrating, or emotional issues related to the accident. The accident led to one week off work, but she has since returned to her usual routine with no significant impact on her daily life or hobbies.

Objective.Physical_Exam: Neck and back demonstrate a full range of movement. No tenderness or signs of lasting damage were noted. Muscles and spine appear to be in good condition.
Objective.Observations: Patient appears well and is recovering positively from the whiplash injury. No signs of long-term damage or degeneration were observed during the examination.

Plan.Treatment: Continue current activities. No specific new treatment interventions are required at this time, given the positive recovery trajectory.
Plan.Follow-Up: Patient is expected to make a full recovery within six months of the accident, with no foreseen long-term impact on work or daily life. Advised to return for a follow-up if symptoms worsen or new concerns arise.
